  "prompt": "How dangerous are corn snakes, and are they venomous?",
  "response": "Corn snakes (Pantherophis guttatus) are non-venomous constrictor snakes. They are not dangerous to humans and are often kept as pets due to their docile nature and manageable size. Corn snakes primarily rely on constriction to subdue their prey, which consists mainly of small mammals and birds.\n\nWhile corn snakes can bite if they feel threatened or are improperly handled, their bites are harmless and typically result in minor injuries, such as a small bruise or scratch. Overall, corn snakes are considered safe and are a popular choice for snake enthusiasts.",
